git status
git branch -d <branch name> This deletes existing branch
chmod u+x modifies the access rights  
sudo temporarily become the superuser
su temporarily become the superuser
chown change file ownership
chgrp change a file's group ownership
git checkout -b <branch name> This creates and switches to new branch

#Directory Permissions
777 rwxrwxrwx No restrictions on permissions.
755 rwxr-xr-x The directory user has full access. Others do too but cannot modify the files nor delete them.
700 rwx------ The directory owner has full access. Nobody else has any rights.
666 rw-re-rw- All users may read and write the file.
644 rw-r--r-- The owner may read and write a file, while all others may only read the file.
600 rw------- The owner may read and write a file. All others have no rights. For keeping files private.


#Keyboard shortcuts
ctrl+l clears the screen
ctrl+s stops all output to the screen.
ctrl+q resumes output to the screen after stopping it with ctrl+s
ctrl+d closes the bash shell

#Moving The cursor
ctrl+a go to the beginning of the line
ctrl+e go to the end of the line
alt+b go left/back one word
ctrl+b go left/back one character
alt+f go right/forward one word
ctrl+f go right/forward one character
ctrl+xx moves the cursor between the beginning and end of a line

#Deleting Text
ctrl+d or delete Delets the character under the cursor
alt+d Deletes all characters after the cursor on the current line
ctrl+h or backspace Deletes the character before the cursor

#Fixing Typos
alt+T Swaps the current word with the previous
ctrl+t Swaps the last two characters before the cursor with each other
ctrl+_ the is to undo your last key press

#Cutting and Pasting
ctrl+w cuts the word before the cursor, adding it to the clipboard
ctrl+k cuts the part of the line editor
ctrl+u cuts part of the line before the cursor
ctrl+y pastes the text. The y here stands for "yank"

#Capitalizing Characters
alt+u capitalize every character from the cursor to the end of current word
alt+l uncapitalize every character from the cursor to the end of current word
alt+c capitalize character under the cursor

#Working With My Command History
alt+r Reverts any changes to a command I've pulled from my history if I've edited it.
ctrl+r Recalls the last command matching the characters I provide
ctrl+o Runs a command I found with ctrl+R
ctrl+g leaves history search mode without running a command

#Switching Keyboard Styles
set -o vi This switches to vi keyboard style
set -o emacs Need I say more?

